1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,414
A new model launches.

2
00:00:01,414 --> 00:00:04,951
The benchmark card says: ninety-two point four percent on M.M.L.U.

3
00:00:04,951 --> 00:00:07,427
You take it back to your own

4
00:00:07,427 --> 00:00:09,196
work — twenty real questions,

5
00:00:09,196 --> 00:00:11,672
the kind of things you actually do

6
00:00:11,672 --> 00:00:15,209
— and it's right maybe sixty percent of the time.

7
00:00:15,209 --> 00:00:15,916
Same model.

8
00:00:15,916 --> 00:00:16,623
Same week.

9
00:00:16,623 --> 00:00:18,392
The two numbers don't agree.

10
00:00:18,392 --> 00:00:20,868
> Here's the part that surprises people:

11
00:00:20,868 --> 00:00:23,344
when the benchmark and your task disagree,

12
00:00:23,344 --> 00:00:26,527
the benchmark is rarely wrong about its own task.

13
00:00:26,527 --> 00:00:28,295
It's just not your task.

14
00:00:28,295 --> 00:00:31,003
There are three places where a benchmark

15
00:00:31,003 --> 00:00:34,484
can drift away from your work, and they stack.

16
00:00:34,484 --> 00:00:36,805
> The first is task shift.

17
00:00:36,805 --> 00:00:39,900
The benchmark might ask: answer this multiple-choice question.

18
00:00:39,900 --> 00:00:42,607
Your work might be: draft a one-paragraph

19
00:00:42,607 --> 00:00:45,315
summary that doesn't drift from the source.

20
00:00:45,315 --> 00:00:47,249
Those are two different skills.

21
00:00:47,249 --> 00:00:49,570
> The second is distribution shift.

22
00:00:49,570 --> 00:00:53,051
The benchmark's input might be a clean textbook stem.

23
00:00:53,051 --> 00:00:56,919
Your input might be a customer email with three typos,

24
00:00:56,919 --> 00:00:59,627
an embedded screenshot, and a half-finished thought.

25
00:00:59,627 --> 00:01:01,948
> The third is scoring shift.

26
00:01:01,948 --> 00:01:04,268
The benchmark might score exact-match accuracy.

27
00:01:04,268 --> 00:01:06,976
You might care whether the draft is

28
00:01:06,976 --> 00:01:09,684
good enough to use without rewriting it.

29
00:01:09,684 --> 00:01:13,552
That's a different question, even when the inputs are identical.

30
00:01:13,552 --> 00:01:17,033
> No single one of these is the villain.

31
00:01:17,033 --> 00:01:19,741
A benchmark can score very high on

32
00:01:19,741 --> 00:01:22,835
its own task and only middling on yours,

33
00:01:22,835 --> 00:01:24,769
and nothing has gone wrong.

34
00:01:24,769 --> 00:01:27,863
The two numbers are just measuring different things.

35
00:01:27,864 --> 00:01:31,663
The best fix for a benchmark-task gap isn't a better benchmark.

36
00:01:31,663 --> 00:01:34,772
It's a small private eval that you build yourself.

37
00:01:34,772 --> 00:01:38,572
> Here's a template that works for a lot of people.

38
00:01:38,572 --> 00:01:39,608
Write thirty questions.

39
00:01:39,608 --> 00:01:42,026
Ten typical ones — the questions you

40
00:01:42,026 --> 00:01:44,444
ask the model on a normal day.

41
00:01:44,444 --> 00:01:46,862
Ten stretch ones — things you'd love

42
00:01:46,862 --> 00:01:49,971
the model to handle but don't quite trust yet.

43
00:01:49,971 --> 00:01:52,389
And ten trap ones — questions where

44
00:01:52,389 --> 00:01:54,462
you've seen the model fail before,

45
00:01:54,462 --> 00:01:56,535
or where it should politely refuse.

46
00:01:56,535 --> 00:01:58,607
> Thirty is a useful number.

47
00:01:58,607 --> 00:02:01,025
It's small enough that you can run

48
00:02:01,025 --> 00:02:03,443
it against any model in about twenty

49
00:02:03,443 --> 00:02:05,861
minutes — roughly forty seconds per answer

50
00:02:05,861 --> 00:02:08,625
if you're skimming and grading on the fly.

51
00:02:08,625 --> 00:02:11,043
And it's large enough that a real

52
00:02:11,043 --> 00:02:13,806
difference between two models will usually show up.

53
00:02:13,806 --> 00:02:15,188
You're not building M.M.L.U.

54
00:02:15,188 --> 00:02:17,951
You're building a sanity check for your work.

55
00:02:17,951 --> 00:02:21,461
The grading rubric matters as much as the questions.

56
00:02:21,461 --> 00:02:24,191
A four-option rubric tends to work better

57
00:02:24,191 --> 00:02:26,531
than a five or a ten,

58
00:02:26,531 --> 00:02:28,870
because it forces you to commit.

59
00:02:28,870 --> 00:02:31,990
> For each answer, pick one: Use as-is.

60
00:02:31,990 --> 00:02:32,770
Light edit.

61
00:02:32,770 --> 00:02:33,160
Rewrite.

62
00:02:33,160 --> 00:02:35,110
Or wrong, refused, or dangerous.

63
00:02:35,110 --> 00:02:37,839
> Then your headline number is the

64
00:02:37,839 --> 00:02:41,739
sum of "use as-is" and "light edit," out of thirty.

65
00:02:41,739 --> 00:02:44,469
In this illustrative example, Model A scores

66
00:02:44,469 --> 00:02:47,978
twenty-two out of thirty and Model B scores eighteen.

67
00:02:47,978 --> 00:02:51,878
That gap means something — to you, on your task.

68
00:02:51,878 --> 00:02:54,608
It's not the same kind of claim

69
00:02:54,608 --> 00:02:57,337
as a benchmark percentage, but it's the

70
00:02:57,337 --> 00:02:59,677
one that actually drives your decision.

71
00:02:59,677 --> 00:03:01,237
> One small caveat.

72
00:03:01,237 --> 00:03:03,967
Re-run your rubric every six weeks —

73
00:03:03,967 --> 00:03:06,696
both on whatever new model has shipped,

74
00:03:06,696 --> 00:03:08,646
and on the rubric itself.

75
00:03:08,646 --> 00:03:12,936
Ask whether the four buckets still capture what you care about.

76
00:03:12,936 --> 00:03:16,056
Your taste drifts faster than the models do.

77
00:03:16,055 --> 00:03:18,710
A public benchmark answers a useful question:

78
00:03:18,710 --> 00:03:22,122
how does this model do on a standard task?

79
00:03:22,122 --> 00:03:24,776
Your private eval answers a different one:

80
00:03:24,776 --> 00:03:27,809
how does this model do on my task?

81
00:03:27,809 --> 00:03:28,947
Both are real.

82
00:03:28,947 --> 00:03:30,084
Both are limited.

83
00:03:30,084 --> 00:03:32,738
And the two can disagree by twenty

84
00:03:32,738 --> 00:03:35,392
points even when both are honestly reported.

85
00:03:35,392 --> 00:03:39,184
> That wraps a small four-video arc on this channel.

86
00:03:39,184 --> 00:03:40,321
Read the benchmark.

87
00:03:40,321 --> 00:03:41,459
Deconstruct the gap.

88
00:03:41,459 --> 00:03:42,975
Test the live answer.

89
00:03:42,975 --> 00:03:47,146
And — when it matters to you — measure for yourself.

90
00:03:47,146 --> 00:03:49,800
The honest version of an AI claim

91
00:03:49,800 --> 00:03:52,454
is usually a smaller, more specific claim,

92
00:03:52,454 --> 00:03:54,350
made against a clearer question.

93
00:03:54,350 --> 00:03:55,487
Thanks for watching.
